WEBVTT

00:00.920 --> 00:13.320
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain. For more information and to find out how you can volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:13.600 --> 00:15.780
Recording by Moira Fogarty.

00:16.500 --> 00:22.580
The Art of War by Sun Tzu. Translated by Lionel Giles.

00:23.760 --> 00:27.060
Part IX. The Army on the March.

00:27.060 --> 00:29.280
Sun Tzu said,

00:57.060 --> 01:04.380
Do not advance to meet it in midstream. It will be best to let half the army get across, and then deliver your attack.

01:05.620 --> 01:11.240
If you are anxious to fight, you should not go to meet the invader near a river which he has to cross.

01:12.300 --> 01:20.860
Mour your craft higher up than the enemy, and facing the sun. Do not move upstream to meet the enemy. So much for river warfare.

01:21.780 --> 01:27.800
In crossing salt marshes, your sole concern should be to get over them quickly, without any delay.

01:29.060 --> 01:39.360
If forced to fight in a salt marsh, you should have water and grass near you and get your back to a clump of trees. So much for operations in salt marshes.

01:39.360 --> 01:50.480
In dry, level country, take up an easily accessible position with rising ground to your right and on your rear, so that the danger may be in front and safety lie behind.

01:51.500 --> 01:53.920
So much for campaigning in flat country.

01:55.240 --> 02:02.360
These are the four useful branches of military knowledge which enabled the Yellow Emperor to vanquish four several sovereigns.

02:03.100 --> 02:07.360
All armies prefer high ground to low, and sunny places to dark.

02:07.360 --> 02:15.860
If you are careful of your men and camp on hard ground, the army will be free from disease of every kind, and this will spell victory.

02:17.060 --> 02:22.200
When you come to a hill or a bank, occupy the sunny side, with the slope on your right rear.

02:23.080 --> 02:29.720
Thus you will at once act for the benefit of your soldiers, and utilize the natural advantages of the ground.

02:30.560 --> 02:40.920
When, in consequence of heavy rains up country, a river which you wish to ford is swollen and flecked with foam, you must wait until it subsides.

02:41.540 --> 02:55.440
Country in which there are precipitous cliffs with torrents running between, deep natural hollows, confined places, tangled thickets, quagmires and crevasses, should be left with all possible speed and not approached.

02:56.560 --> 03:00.840
While we keep away from such places, we should get the enemy to approach them.

03:01.020 --> 03:04.340
While we face them, we should let the enemy have them on his rear.

03:05.860 --> 03:16.180
If in the neighborhood of your camp there should be any hilly country, ponds surrounded by aquatic grass, hollow basins filled with reeds, or woods with thick undergrowth,

03:16.800 --> 03:24.220
they must be carefully routed out and searched, for these are places where men in ambush or insidious spies are likely to be lurking.

03:25.240 --> 03:31.360
When the enemy is close at hand and remains quiet, he is relying on the natural strength of his position.

03:32.280 --> 03:37.220
When he keeps aloof and tries to provoke a battle, he is anxious for the other side to advance.

03:38.600 --> 03:42.500
If his place of encampment is easy of access, he is tendering a bait.

03:43.840 --> 03:47.540
Movement amongst the trees of a forest shows that the enemy is advancing.

03:48.480 --> 03:54.780
The appearance of a number of screens in the midst of thick grass means that the enemy wants to make us suspicious.

03:56.600 --> 03:59.940
The rising of birds in their flight is the sign of an ambuscade.

04:00.640 --> 04:03.560
Startled beasts indicate that a sudden attack is coming.

04:05.120 --> 04:10.080
When there is dust rising in a high column, it is the sign of chariots advancing.

04:11.040 --> 04:16.180
When the dust is low, but spread over a wide area, it betokens the approach of infantry.

04:16.180 --> 04:22.240
When it branches out in different directions, it shows that parties have been sent to collect firewood.

04:23.140 --> 04:28.680
A few clouds of dust moving to and fro signify that the army is encamping.

04:29.060 --> 04:33.720
Humble words and increased preparations are signs that the enemy is about to advance.

04:34.420 --> 04:39.400
Violent language and driving forward as if to the attack are signs that he will retreat.

04:40.560 --> 04:44.260
When the light chariots come out first and take up a position on the wings,

04:44.260 --> 04:47.440
it is a sign that the enemy is forming for battle.

04:48.640 --> 04:52.720
Peace proposals unaccompanied by a sworn covenant indicate a plot.

04:54.300 --> 05:00.020
When there is much running about and the soldiers fall into rank, it means that the critical moment has come.

05:00.960 --> 05:04.760
When some are seen advancing and some retreating, it is a lure.

05:06.080 --> 05:09.940
When the soldiers stand leaning on their spears, they are faint from want of food.

05:09.940 --> 05:15.920
If those who are sent to draw water begin by drinking themselves, the army is suffering from thirst.

05:17.000 --> 05:22.560
If the enemy sees an advantage to be gained and makes no effort to secure it, the soldiers are exhausted.

05:23.580 --> 05:27.180
If birds gather on any spot, it is unoccupied.

05:27.600 --> 05:29.840
Clamor by night betokens nervousness.

05:31.320 --> 05:34.880
If there is a disturbance in the camp, the general's authority is weak.

05:35.500 --> 05:39.700
If the banners and flags are shifted about, sedition is afoot.

05:40.300 --> 05:44.060
If the officers are angry, it means that the men are weary.

05:45.820 --> 05:49.880
When an army feeds its horses with grain and kills its cattle for food,

05:50.280 --> 05:55.660
and when the men do not hang their cooking pots over the campfires showing that they will not return to their tents,

05:56.420 --> 05:59.340
you may know that they are determined to fight to the death.

06:00.460 --> 06:08.980
The sight of men whispering together in small knots or speaking in subdued tones points to disaffection amongst the rank and file.

06:10.260 --> 06:13.980
Too frequent rewards signify that the enemy is at the end of his resources.

06:14.720 --> 06:18.080
Too many punishments betray a condition of dire distress.

06:19.580 --> 06:26.040
To begin by bluster, but afterwards to take fright at the enemy's numbers, shows a supreme lack of intelligence.

06:27.060 --> 06:33.000
When envoys are sent with compliments in their mouths, it is a sign that the enemy wishes for a truce.

06:34.120 --> 06:42.440
If the enemy's troops march up angrily and remain facing ours for a long time without either joining battle or taking themselves off again,

06:42.920 --> 06:46.680
the situation is one that demands great vigilance and circumspection.

06:47.760 --> 06:52.080
If our troops are no more in number than the enemy, that is amply sufficient.

06:52.340 --> 06:54.880
It only means that no direct attack can be made.

06:54.880 --> 07:03.180
What we can do is simply to concentrate all our available strength, keep a close watch on the enemy, and obtain reinforcements.

07:04.260 --> 07:10.240
He who exercises no forethought but makes light of his opponents is sure to be captured by them.

07:11.440 --> 07:16.780
If soldiers are punished before they have grown attached to you, they will not prove submissive.

07:17.420 --> 07:20.680
And, unless submissive, they will be practically useless.

07:21.520 --> 07:28.160
If, when the soldiers have become attached to you, punishments are not enforced, they will still be useless.

07:29.480 --> 07:36.440
Therefore, soldiers must be treated in the first instance with humanity, but kept under control by means of iron discipline.

07:37.200 --> 07:39.280
This is a certain road to victory.

07:40.760 --> 07:45.880
If, in training soldiers, commands are habitually enforced, the army will be well disciplined.

07:46.420 --> 07:48.920
If not, its discipline will be bad.

07:48.920 --> 07:56.680
If a general shows confidence in his men, but always insists on his orders being obeyed, the gain will be mutual.

08:03.840 --> 08:08.160
Sun Tzu said, we may distinguish six kinds of terrain.

08:08.160 --> 08:25.600
To wit, one, accessible ground, two, entangling ground, three, temporizing ground, four, narrow passes, five, precipitous heights, six, positions at a great distance from the enemy.

08:26.760 --> 08:30.440
Ground which can be freely traversed by both sides is called accessible.

08:31.060 --> 08:39.500
With regard to ground of this nature, be before the enemy in occupying the raised and sunny spots, and carefully guard your line of supplies.

08:40.400 --> 08:42.920
Then you will be able to fight with advantage.

08:44.020 --> 08:48.600
Ground which can be abandoned but is hard to re-occupy is called entangling.

08:49.680 --> 08:54.920
From a position of this sort, if the enemy is unprepared, you may sally forth and defeat him.

08:54.920 --> 09:03.900
But if the enemy is prepared for your coming and you fail to defeat him, then, return being impossible, disaster will ensue.

09:04.720 --> 09:10.600
When the position is such that neither side will gain by making the first move, it is called temporizing ground.

09:11.800 --> 09:22.800
In a position of this sort, even though the enemy should offer us an attractive bait, it will be advisable not to stir forth, but rather to retreat, thus enticing the enemy in his turn.

09:23.720 --> 09:28.560
Then, when part of his army has come out, we may deliver our attack with advantage.

09:30.280 --> 09:37.820
With regard to narrow passes, if you can occupy them first, let them be strongly garrisoned and await the advent of the enemy.

09:38.700 --> 09:46.780
Should the army forestall you in occupying a pass, do not go after him if the pass is fully garrisoned, but only if it is weakly garrisoned.

09:47.340 --> 09:56.340
With regard to precipitous heights, if you are beforehand with your adversary, you should occupy the raised and sunny spots and there wait for him to come up.

09:57.700 --> 10:04.420
If the enemy has occupied them before you, do not follow him, but retreat and try to entice him away.

10:06.100 --> 10:15.680
If you are situated at a great distance from the enemy and the strength of the two armies is equal, it is not easy to provoke a battle and fighting will be to your disadvantage.

10:16.520 --> 10:24.620
These six are the principles connected with Earth. The general who has attained a responsible post must be careful to study them.

10:25.560 --> 10:33.820
Now, an army is exposed to six several calamities, not arising from natural causes, but from faults for which the general is responsible.

10:33.820 --> 10:48.180
These are 1. Flight, 2. Insubordination, 3. Collapse, 4. Ruin, 5. Disorganization, 6. Route.

10:49.880 --> 10:57.560
Other conditions being equal, if one force is hurled against another ten times its size, the result will be the flight of the former.

10:57.560 --> 11:04.340
When the common soldiers are too strong and their officers too weak, the result is insubordination.

11:05.060 --> 11:10.200
When the officers are too strong and the common soldiers too weak, the result is collapse.

11:11.500 --> 11:18.560
When the higher officers are angry and insubordinate and on meeting the enemy give battle on their own account from a feeling of resentment,

11:19.380 --> 11:24.940
before the commander-in-chief can tell whether or not he is in a position to fight, the result is ruin.

11:26.040 --> 11:31.680
When the general is weak and without authority, when his orders are not clear and distinct,

11:32.240 --> 11:41.920
when there are no fixed duties assigned to officers and men, and the ranks are formed in a slovenly haphazard manner, the result is utter disorganization.

11:43.360 --> 11:49.880
When a general, unable to estimate the enemy's strength, allows an inferior force to engage a larger one,

11:49.880 --> 11:58.020
or hurls a weak detachment against a powerful one, and neglects to place picked soldiers in the front rank, the result must be route.

11:59.740 --> 12:06.180
These are six ways of courting defeat which must be carefully noted by the general who has attained a responsible post.

12:07.380 --> 12:13.340
The natural formation of the country is the soldier's best ally, but a power of estimating the adversary,

12:13.340 --> 12:22.460
of controlling the forces of victory, and of shrewdly calculating difficulties, dangers, and distances, constitutes the test of a great general.

12:23.500 --> 12:28.780
He who knows these things and in fighting puts his knowledge into practice will win his battles.

12:29.600 --> 12:33.620
He who knows them not, nor practices them, will surely be defeated.

12:34.680 --> 12:40.100
If fighting is sure to result in victory, then you must fight, even though the ruler forbid it.

12:40.100 --> 12:45.620
If fighting will not result in victory, then you must not fight, even at the ruler's bidding.

12:47.000 --> 12:52.080
The general who advances without coveting fame and retreats without fearing disgrace,

12:52.600 --> 12:59.020
whose only thought is to protect his country and do good service for his sovereign, is the jewel of the kingdom.

13:00.800 --> 13:05.320
Regard your soldiers as your children, and they will follow you into the deepest valleys.

13:05.320 --> 13:11.140
Look upon them as your own beloved sons, and they will stand by you even unto death.

13:12.400 --> 13:20.060
If, however, you are indulgent, but unable to make your authority felt, kind-hearted, but unable to enforce your commands,

13:20.620 --> 13:26.420
and incapable, moreover, of quelling disorder, then your soldiers must be likened to spoilt children.

13:27.000 --> 13:29.480
They are useless for any practical purpose.

13:30.800 --> 13:37.280
If we know that our own men are in a condition to attack but are unaware that the enemy is not open to attack,

13:37.560 --> 13:40.360
we have gone only halfway towards victory.

13:41.580 --> 13:47.920
If we know that the enemy is open to attack but are unaware that our own men are not in a condition to attack,

13:48.320 --> 13:51.020
we have gone only halfway towards victory.

13:52.300 --> 13:58.520
If we know that the enemy is open to attack and also know that our men are in a condition to attack,

13:58.520 --> 14:06.560
But are unaware that the nature of the ground makes fighting impracticable, we have still only gone halfway towards victory.

14:07.600 --> 14:15.360
Hence the experienced soldier, once in motion, is never bewildered. Once he has broken camp, he is never at a loss.

14:16.180 --> 14:22.180
Hence the saying, If you know the enemy and know yourself, your victory will not stand in doubt.

14:22.180 --> 14:27.760
If you know heaven and know earth, you may make your victory complete.

